{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_019joMq1YA2w6nNxFbizkQyk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that our CSS starts the views with `opacity: 0` and the `view-visible` class sets it to 1. But the test is checking opacity before the transition may have completed. I need to wait for the repo cards to be visible first, then check opacity. Actually the test does `await expect(page.locator('.repo-card').first()).toBeVisible()` but the opacity of the parent div may be 0 during the transition. Let me adjust the test to wait for the view-visible class.\n\nActually, looking more carefully — the test says `await expect(page.locator('.repo-card').first()).toBeVisible()`. \n\nThe real problem is that Playwright's `toBeVisible()` checks the element itself for visibility, not its parent's opacity, so a child element can appear visible even when its parent has `opacity: 0`. That's why the test passes but the opacity check fails — I need to ensure the parent view actually has the `view-visible` class applied before checking anything. opacity: 1`. So the issue is a CSS specificity problem — the ID selector on `#repo-view` has higher specificity than the `.view-visible` class, so the opacity stays at 0 even when the class is added. I need to restructure the CSS to fix this, either by increasing the specificity of `.view-visible` or removing the opacity rule from the ID selector.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1151,"cache_read_input_tokens":113315,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1151},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"27f9d074-e552-4076-906c-5830713f721a","uuid":"529e6232-4d62-402f-86a2-433ccce2dd4c"}
